{"description": "Implement React auth frontend", "prompt": "You are implementing the auth/RBAC frontend for the FieldServe React app. Write all files under /home/nico/Work/task-w2t70/repo/frontend/. Do NOT run any commands — only write files.

## Existing context

The project uses React 18, TypeScript, Vite, React Router v6, TanStack Query v5, Zustand, Tailwind CSS, and Vitest. Existing files:

**`src/api/client.ts`** — fetch wrapper with `api.get/post/put/patch/delete`, handles normalized error contract `{error: {code, message, field_errors, request_id}}`. Exports `ApiError` class and `api` object. Uses `credentials: "include"`. Base path `/api/v1`.

**`src/main.tsx`** — renders App with QueryClientProvider + BrowserRouter.

**`src/App.tsx`** — Routes: /login -> LoginPage, /customer/* -> RouteGuard > CustomerLayout, /provider/* -> RouteGuard > ProviderLayout, /admin/* -> RouteGuard > AdminLayout, * -> NotFoundPage. Each layout renders an Outlet.

**`src/pages/LoginPage.tsx`** — Form shell with username/password fields and "Sign In" button. Not wired to API.

**`src/components/RouteGuard.tsx`** — Placeholder that renders children unconditionally.

**`src/layouts/{Customer,Provider,Admin}Layout.tsx`** — Shell layouts with nav bar showing "FieldServe — {Role}" and a Dashboard link. Each renders Outlet.

**`src/pages/{customer,provider,admin}/DashboardPage.tsx`** — Placeholder text like "Customer Dashboard".

**`src/pages/NotFoundPage.tsx`** — 404 page with "404" and "Page not found" text.

**`vite.config.ts`** — React plugin, path alias `@` -> `src/`, proxy `/api` to `http://api:8080`, vitest with jsdom.

**`package.json`** — Has zustand in dependencies.

## API contract

The backend provides these auth endpoints:

**POST /auth/login**
Request: `{"username": "admin", "password": "admin123"}`
Success 200: `{"user": {"id": "uuid", "username": "admin", "email": "admin@fieldserve.local", "roles": ["administrator"]}}`
Sets HttpOnly cookie automatically (browser handles it).
Failure 401: `{"error": {"code": "invalid_credentials", "message": "Invalid username or password."}}`

**POST /auth/logout**
Success 200: `{"message": "Logged out."}`
Clears HttpOnly cookie.

**GET /auth/me**
Success 200: `{"user": {"id": "uuid", "username": "admin", "email": "admin@fieldserve.local", "roles": ["administrator"]}}`
Failure 401: `{"error": {"code": "unauthenticated", "message": "Authentication required."}}`

**POST /auth/bootstrap-admin**
Request: `{"username": "...", "password": "...", "email": "..."}`
Success 201: `{"user": {...}}`
Failure 409: `{"error": {"code": "admin_exists", "message": "An administrator already exists."}}`

The cookie is HttpOnly so JavaScript can't read it. Auth state is bootstrapped by calling GET /auth/me on app load.

## What to implement

### 1. `src/api/client.ts` (KEEP AS IS — no changes needed)

### 2. `src/stores/auth.ts` (NEW)

Zustand store for auth state. DO NOT store tokens (they're in HttpOnly cookies).

```typescript
import { create } from "zustand";
import { api, ApiError } from "../api/client";

export interface AuthUser {
  id: string;
  username: string;
  email: string;
  roles: string[];
}

interface AuthState {
  user: AuthUser | null;
  loading: boolean;
  error: string | null;

  bootstrap: () => Promise<void>;
  login: (username: string, password: string) => Promise<AuthUser>;
  logout: () => Promise<void>;
}
```

Implementation:
- `bootstrap()`: calls GET /auth/me. On success, sets user. On 401, sets user to null (not logged in). On other error, sets user to null. Always sets loading=false when done.
- `login(username, password)`: calls POST /auth/login with body. On success, sets user from response and returns it. On failure, throws the error (let the caller handle it).
- `logout()`: calls POST /auth/logout. Sets user to null.

The store starts with `loading: true, user: null, error: null`.

Helper function exported from the store:
```typescript
export function hasRole(user: AuthUser | null, role: string): boolean {
  return user?.roles.includes(role) ?? false;
}

export function primaryRole(user: AuthUser | null): string | null {
  if (!user) return null;
  // Return the most specific role
  if (user.roles.includes("administrator")) return "administrator";
  if (user.roles.includes("provider")) return "provider";
  if (user.roles.includes("customer")) return "customer";
  return null;
}

export function roleHomePath(role: string | null): string {
  switch (role) {
    case "administrator": return "/admin";
    case "provider": return "/provider";
    case "customer": return "/customer";
    default: return "/login";
  }
}
```

### 3. `src/App.tsx` (REPLACE)

Add auth bootstrapping. On mount, call `bootstrap()`. While loading, show a simple centered loading indicator. Once loaded, render routes.

The route structure stays the same but uses the updated RouteGuard with role props:

```tsx
<Routes>
  <Route path="/login" element={<LoginPage />} />

  <Route path="/customer/*" element={<RouteGuard role="customer"><CustomerLayout /></RouteGuard>}>
    <Route index element={<CustomerDashboardPage />} />
  </Route>

  <Route path="/provider/*" element={<RouteGuard role="provider"><ProviderLayout /></RouteGuard>}>
    <Route index element={<ProviderDashboardPage />} />
  </Route>

  <Route path="/admin/*" element={<RouteGuard role="administrator"><AdminLayout /></RouteGuard>}>
    <Route index element={<AdminDashboardPage />} />
  </Route>

  <Route path="/" element={<RootRedirect />} />
  <Route path="*" element={<NotFoundPage />} />
</Routes>
```

Add a `RootRedirect` component that redirects to the user's portal if logged in, or /login if not.

### 4. `src/components/RouteGuard.tsx` (REPLACE)

Real auth + role guard:
```tsx
interface RouteGuardProps {
  role: string;
  children: ReactNode;
}
```

- Gets user and loading from auth store
- If loading, show spinner
- If no user (not authenticated), redirect to /login with `<Navigate to="/login" replace />`
- If user doesn't have the required role, show a "403 Forbidden — Insufficient permissions" page (don't redirect to login — the user IS authenticated but lacks the role)
- If user has the required role, render children

### 5. `src/pages/LoginPage.tsx` (REPLACE)

Wire to real API:
- If user is already logged in (from auth store), redirect to their portal using `roleHomePath(primaryRole(user))`
- Username + password fields with labels (keep the label htmlFor="username" and htmlFor="password" for accessibility, these are used in tests)
- On submit: call `login(username, password)` from auth store
- On success: navigate to `roleHomePath(primaryRole(user))`
- On failure: show inline error message from the ApiError
- Show loading state on button during submission
- Keep the "FieldServe" heading and "Sign In" button text
- Keep Tailwind styling similar to current

### 6. `src/layouts/CustomerLayout.tsx` (REPLACE)

Add logout button to nav:
```tsx
import { useNavigate } from "react-router-dom";
import { useAuthStore } from "../stores/auth";

function CustomerLayout() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();
  const { user, logout } = useAuthStore();

  const handleLogout = async () => {
    await logout();
    navigate("/login");
  };

  return (
    <div className="min-h-screen bg-gray-50">
      <nav className="border-b bg-white px-6 py-3">
        <div className="flex items-center justify-between">
          <span className="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">
            FieldServe — Customer
          </span>
          <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
            <Link to="/customer" className="text-sm text-gray-600 hover:text-gray-900">Dashboard</Link>
            <span className="text-sm text-gray-400">{user?.username}</span>
            <button onClick={handleLogout} className="text-sm text-red-600 hover:text-red-800">Logout</button>
          </div>
        </div>
      </nav>
      <main className="p-6"><Outlet /></main>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 7. `src/layouts/ProviderLayout.tsx` (REPLACE)
Same pattern as CustomerLayout but with "FieldServe — Provider" title.

### 8. `src/layouts/AdminLayout.tsx` (REPLACE)
Same pattern but with "FieldServe — Admin" title.

### 9. `src/__tests__/App.test.tsx` (REPLACE)

Update tests to work with auth. The key challenge: routes are now behind auth guards. Tests need to mock the auth store.

Use vitest mocking to mock the auth store. The approach:

```tsx
import { vi, describe, it, expect, beforeEach } from "vitest";
import { render, screen } from "@testing-library/react";
import { MemoryRouter } from "react-router-dom";
import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from "@tanstack/react-query";
```

Mock the auth store module:
```tsx
// Mock the auth store
const mockAuthStore = {
  user: null as AuthUser | null,
  loading: false,
  error: null,
  bootstrap: vi.fn(),
  login: vi.fn(),
  logout: vi.fn(),
};

vi.mock("../stores/auth", () => ({
  useAuthStore: vi.fn((selector?: any) => {
    if (typeof selector === "function") return selector(mockAuthStore);
    return mockAuthStore;
  }),
  hasRole: (user: any, role: string) => user?.roles?.includes(role) ?? false,
  primaryRole: (user: any) => {
    if (!user) return null;
    if (user.roles.includes("administrator")) return "administrator";
    if (user.roles.includes("provider")) return "provider";
    if (user.roles.includes("customer")) return "customer";
    return null;
  },
  roleHomePath: (role: string | null) => {
    switch (role) {
      case "administrator": return "/admin";
      case "provider": return "/provider";
      case "customer": return "/customer";
      default: return "/login";
    }
  },
}));
```

Tests:

a) **"renders login page at /login"** — set mockAuthStore.user = null, loading = false. Render at /login. Assert FieldServe heading, Username label, Password label, Sign In button exist.

b) **"redirects unauthenticated user from /customer to /login"** — user = null, loading = false. Render at /customer. Assert login page is shown (redirected).

